        "direction": null,
        "relation": null,
        "text": "Erdős #567 (?, AMS 5). STATEMENT: $Q_3$ is the 3-dimensional hypercube graph (8 vertices, 12 edges). Vertices are 3-bit vectors. Two vertices are adjacent iff they differ in exactly one bit. FORMAL: erdos_567: answer(sorry) ↔ IsRamseySizeLinear Q3; erdos_567: answer(sorry) ↔ IsRamseySizeLinear K33; erdos_567: answer(sorry) ↔ IsRamseySizeLinear H5 KNOWN/REMARKS: # Erdős Problem 567 Let $G$ be either $Q_3$ or $K_{3,3}$ or $H_5$ (the last formed by adding two vertex-disjoint chords to $C_5$). Is it true that, if $H$ has $m$ edges and no isolated vertices, then $$ \\hat{r}(G,H) \\ll m? $$ In other words, is $G$ Ramsey size linear? A special case of Problem 566. *Reference:* erdosproblems.com/567 [EFRS93] Erdős, Faudree, Rousseau and Schelp, _Ramsey size linear RELATED: [566] OEIS: []",
